<div id="review_88737084" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/88737084" />
    <a title="Adam Dalva" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3263980-adam-dalva"><img alt="Adam Dalva" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1452476649p2/3263980.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/88737084?book_show_action=true">Feb 08, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Adam Dalva" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Adam Dalva" href="/user/show/3263980-adam-dalva">Adam Dalva</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer88737084" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2231215626619144577">Potent oral history (with some incisive commentary) by Murakami on the Sarin Gas attack in the Tokyo subway - 34 commuters detail their experiences, with much of the shock focusing on the mundane (a man still buying milk after he&apos;s badly poisoned). There&apos;s a metronomic beauty to the repetition of this section, which makes it such a shame that this version is severely abridged from the Japanese, which has twice the number of victims. The book then makes a remarkable pivot and treats members of th</span>
  <span id="freeText2231215626619144577" style="display:none">Potent oral history (with some incisive commentary) by Murakami on the Sarin Gas attack in the Tokyo subway - 34 commuters detail their experiences, with much of the shock focusing on the mundane (a man still buying milk after he's badly poisoned). There's a metronomic beauty to the repetition of this section, which makes it such a shame that this version is severely abridged from the Japanese, which has twice the number of victims. The book then makes a remarkable pivot and treats members of the Aum Shinrikyo cult w/ the same focus and care. Here there are forced LSD trips, ECT shocks, and many other horrors, but the two sides end up forming a dynamic, frightening whole.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2231215626619144577" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


