<div id="review_2265159438" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2265159438" />
    <a title="Widyanto Gunadi" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/49008614-widyanto-gunadi"><img alt="Widyanto Gunadi" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1604538989p2/49008614.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2265159438?book_show_action=true">Feb 08, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Widyanto Gunadi" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Widyanto Gunadi" href="/user/show/49008614-widyanto-gunadi">Widyanto Gunadi</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780375703881" href="/book/show/15225517-underground">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2265159438" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5407837545821597390">Haruki Murakami&apos;s journalistic effort in recording a daring and controversial subject in relation to the hazardous Japanese cult organization led by Aum, an esoteric figure behind Aum Shinrikyo is a masterfully written, heartrending book. In this nonfiction work, Murakami-san has interviewed several victims of the nationally shocking, chemical-fueled terrorist attack carried out in a Tokyo subway train station, back in 1995. He gave us, readers, fairly neutral point of view and coverage of the w</span>
  <span id="freeText5407837545821597390" style="display:none">Haruki Murakami's journalistic effort in recording a daring and controversial subject in relation to the hazardous Japanese cult organization led by Aum, an esoteric figure behind Aum Shinrikyo is a masterfully written, heartrending book. In this nonfiction work, Murakami-san has interviewed several victims of the nationally shocking, chemical-fueled terrorist attack carried out in a Tokyo subway train station, back in 1995. He gave us, readers, fairly neutral point of view and coverage of the whole topic, derivatively taken from all of these truthful and meticulously accurate conversational accounts with the survivors of the horrendous accident as well as the former members of the mysterious religious sorority. Upon a complete reading of this journalism literature, we get to see some pivotal, requisite facets of Japanese conscience and psyche. As a society with quite a fanatic obsession for work and a high rate of suicides resulted from acute depression, no wonder that some Japanese people are always in search of a higher calling and meanings behind their seemingly pointless and repetitively monotonous, boring everyday existence. Thus, in the pilgrimage to find a spiritual comfort to escape the unbearable constant boredom which befell them, ethereal concepts such as one offered by Aum Shinrikyo, has gathered quite a large number of devout followers without knowing of the true intent of its notorious leader, which was later revealed, as to led them astray into doing a nationwide infamously condemned criminal charade. This book has an urgently potent transformative power to challenge and change the stereotypical worldviews commonly shared by many casually knowledgable visitors of Japan, as it will expose you to one of the Land of the Rising Sun's undercover hidden truths. Conclusively, if you so loved Japan and its culture, and wanted to read something so thrillingly thoughtful, albeit heartwrenching timeline, of the East Asian country, do pick up Underground at your nearest local bookstore.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5407837545821597390" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


