<div id="review_2430985230" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2430985230" />
    <a title="Rusalka" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6163718-rusalka"><img alt="Rusalka" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1591511894p2/6163718.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2430985230?book_show_action=true">Jan 17, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Rusalka" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Rusalka" href="/user/show/6163718-rusalka">Rusalka</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6163718-rusalka?shelf=around-the-world">around-the-world</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6163718-rusalka?shelf=japan">japan</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6163718-rusalka?shelf=translation">translation</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6163718-rusalka?shelf=ylto-group-theme-reads">ylto-group-theme-reads</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6163718-rusalka?shelf=own">own</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6163718-rusalka?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2430985230" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer749327962498807603">I really love Murakami as a novelist. But he needs to stay as that. He is not a journalist. As the almost 7 months to read this book will attest.<br/><br/>Murakami takes a really interesting subject and makes it... well... boring. The repetitive nature of his interviews with survivors, which really shouldn&apos;t be. The preachy, pseudo-psych, pseudo-philosophy essay in the middle which is peppered with &quot;I&apos;m just a novelist but&quot; which undermines him and makes him look arrogant at the same time. The best part o</span>
  <span id="freeText749327962498807603" style="display:none">I really love Murakami as a novelist. But he needs to stay as that. He is not a journalist. As the almost 7 months to read this book will attest.<br /><br />Murakami takes a really interesting subject and makes it... well... boring. The repetitive nature of his interviews with survivors, which really shouldn't be. The preachy, pseudo-psych, pseudo-philosophy essay in the middle which is peppered with "I'm just a novelist but" which undermines him and makes him look arrogant at the same time. The best part of the book, and why I kept reading in case it was better, was the interviews with the ex-cult members. Murakami directs the interviews and challenges the interviewees more. And they portray different experiences to each other, which is actually interesting.<br /><br />And here is where I display my own bias. While I found the crimes horrifying, and the descriptions of the events terrible, I had huge trouble sympathising and understanding the victims from my own cultural biases. <br /><br />I cannot understand people who were in the middle of a medical/terrorist emergency walking or sometimes crawling to work out of an inbuilt obligation to do so, and possibly exposing coworkers to toxic gas as a result. I didn't get people watching the news in tearooms of their exact train, hearing descriptions of symptoms, going "well I can't breathe or can't see, but I'll keep on working!" instead of going to hospital. <br />I couldn't understand being on the train hours earlier to work as you had to work 3-4 hours a day for free to keep your job. I can't understand the appeal to authority that no emergency services took real control, or the fact that it was a vaguely rogue uni professor who got the word out that it was sarin and how to treat it, and that there was no comeuppance for the chaos or any lessons learnt from the event due to the deference to authority. <br />I cannot understand people who's lives are so regimented that they state which carriage of a train they get into every day and which exact seat they sit in. EVERY DAY. It blows my mind, and it is just so outside my experience, and shows why I could not as an Australian ever be a salaryman in Japan as much as I think it's a good idea some days.<br /><br />And that is good. I had a non-rose-coloured glasses look into Japanese life which I needed. Murakami states that Japan needed this too because of that appeal to authority, and that need to socially regulate everything to the chair on the train you sit on everyday, that they needed to examine those they let fester in their society as just viewing them as outside society and a bit odd. <br /><br />And while I respect and agree with all that, fuck, it was boring.</span>
  <a data-text-id="749327962498807603" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


