    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2778743578" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2778743578" />
    <a title="Gayathri" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/39595268-gayathri"><img alt="Gayathri" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1625480899p2/39595268.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2778743578?book_show_action=true">May 03, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Gayathri" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Gayathri" href="/user/show/39595268-gayathri">Gayathri</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/13067199-underground">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/39595268-gayathri?shelf=murakami">murakami</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/39595268-gayathri?shelf=nonfiction">nonfiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2778743578" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4212785951512876206">Usually when we read or hear about catastrophes, we do so in numbers; so-and-so number of people fatally injured in so-and-so event etc. News of these events do affect us, but we do not fully realize the impact of such casualties. Another number gets added to the list and life goes on as ever. Rarely any of us take the time to think about the individuals who are affected by such events. And this book is an honest attempt at bringing forth stories of such individuals and how their lives are chang</span>
  <span id="freeText4212785951512876206" style="display:none">Usually when we read or hear about catastrophes, we do so in numbers; so-and-so number of people fatally injured in so-and-so event etc. News of these events do affect us, but we do not fully realize the impact of such casualties. Another number gets added to the list and life goes on as ever. Rarely any of us take the time to think about the individuals who are affected by such events. And this book is an honest attempt at bringing forth stories of such individuals and how their lives are changed for the worse through no fault of their own. <br /><br />This book feels like a straightforward stating of the facts. About 60-65% of the book contains interviews of the sarin gas attack victims; what their lives were like before and how their lives changed forever after the attack. It speaks about the physical and psychological aftereffects that the victims carry with them even years after the attack. These individual stories, though seemingly repetitive about the effects it had on them, provide an entirely new perspective about these catastrophes. They stop being mere numbers on the news and change the way we perceive these fatalities, man made or otherwise. <br /><br />Besides interviewing the gas attack victims, Murakami also interviewed a few members of the Aum Shinrikyo cult to understand what drove these people to join a religious cult. I found these interviews to be very interesting. They are really smart people, who felt alienated from the rest of the world, who wanted to find meaning in their lives. These interviews speak about how they came across Aum Shinrikyo, where they finally felt belonged, found like-minded people and naturally stayed there, and also about both the positive and negative effects it had on them.<br /><br />This is not a usual Murakami book with magical realism et al. He's made an honest attempt in collating the interviews and presenting them as is, without bias or adding any kind of seasoning to make it more appetizing. This simplicity is what I love about this book. Just straightforward, simple stories of everyday people.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4212785951512876206" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

